I believe that chess should be taught in elementary schools. For years, the school system in the USSR had chess instruction. The USSR did this because it wanted to develop grandmasters for international prestige. To this day, many great players are Russian.

My reasons are not the same as the Russian one. I think chess should be taught because it encourages thinking on the part of children. They learn many things in chess. They learn how to calculate positional advantages. They learn strategy and tactics. And they learm about spatial development. If they play chess by the clock, the game teaches time management. In addition, chess is inexpensive, requiring only boards and pieces instead og courts and fields.

Some may argue that chess is just a game and the educational system should be more serious. I  argue that chess has many benefits, as mentioned above. Also, chess teaches sportsmanship and can be played by anyone. This eliminates the elitism associated with team sports, where jocks are kings. A little girl or a young child could defeat a big strong quarterback or a tall center.

In conclusion, chess offers many educational benefits and should be incorporated into the school curriculum for all to learn and enjoy.
